\section{Electron tunneling rate beyond Fermi's golden rule}
In many cases, electron tunneling rate from the dot into the
electrodes is found from Fermi's golden rule.
Coupling of the dot level
$\epsilon$ to the electrodes controlled by an external gate voltage $V_G$ can be conveniently described by the
(retarded) self-energy $\Sigma(E)$, $E$ is a quasiparticle energy. The standard perturbative
Fermi's golden rule approach corresponds to approximating the tunneling
rate $\Gamma$ by $\Gamma\approx-2{\mathop{\mathrm{Im}}\nolimits}\Sigma(\epsilon)$.
This approximation is valid provided that the energy dependence
of $\Sigma(E)$ near $E=\epsilon$ is smooth on the scale of
$\Gamma$.

